  "prompt": "How can I be sure people won't steal my idea during a pitch?",
  "response": "Here are some ways to protect your idea during a pitch:\n\n1. Use Non-Disclosure Agreements (NDAs)\n- Have participants sign before sharing details\n- Provides legal protection against idea theft\n\n2. Limit specific details initially\n- Give a high-level overview\n- Protect core proprietary elements\n\n3. File provisional patent applications\n- Establishes early legal claim\n- Provides temporary patent protection\n\n4. Build credibility and reputation\n- Strong track record makes stealing less appealing\n- Demonstrate execution capability\n\n5. Practice selective disclosure\n- Share just enough to generate interest\n- Withhold critical implementation details\n\n6. Consider intellectual property registration\n- Trademarks\n- Copyrights\n- Patents\n\n7. Research potential investors/partners\n- Check reputation\n- Seek recommendations\n- Use trusted networks\n\n8. Document your idea's evolution\n- Keep dated records\n- Maintain development documentation\n\n9. Practice professional pitching\n- Confident, controlled presentation\n- Focus on your unique execution strategy\n\n10. Trust your instincts\n- If something feels uncomfortable, pause\n- Be willing to walk away from potential opportunities\n\nUltimately, execution matters more than the initial idea.",
